&lt;p&gt;The Human Rights Institute&amp;nbsp;proudly presents our Spring&amp;nbsp;event series on:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Activism Against Authoritarianism&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This series is co-sponsored by:&amp;nbsp;Columbia Law Students Human Rights Association, Columbia Journal of Transnational Law, and the Columbia Human Rights Law Review&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We&amp;nbsp;invite&amp;nbsp;you to join us at our third event&amp;nbsp;for a discussion&amp;nbsp;with:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Meena Jagannath, Director of Global Programs, Movement Law Lab&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Topic:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;Fighting autocracy in the US and globally requires building a global movement infrastructure. Activists need to understand how power works globally, and build power to countervail oligarchy. Join us for a dialogue with Meena Jagannath, Director of Global Programs at Movement Law Lab, who will discuss why activists need to de-exceptionalize the United States, and grow networks of solidarity for collective learning and work.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
